HOMEWORK 4¶

This report concerns a Gradient Boosted Tree model trained on the Heart Attack dataset. A usual train/test split was performed - the explanations are executed on the test set.

CP (Exercise 2 and 3)¶

Here, restecg displays the desired property (ex. 3) restecg stands for resting electrocardiographic results, which are results of a test that can detect abnormalities including arrhythmias and evidence of coronary heart disease. It is discrete, having values 0,1 or 2. Because the explanations are local, it is easy to imagine that for some groups, the test result might have a different incluence.

all variables

Exercise 2 answer: the explanations are more or less consistent across samples, we can see for example that cholesterol explanations exhibit significant variability. As this is a tree model, we can see smoothed discontinuities in the graphs.

PDP¶

original model

Exercise 4 answer: The CP and PDP explanations seem consistent, with mild variabiliy. Because the trends for every datapoint are similar in CP (or at least most of them), PDP is consistent with the individual CP instances.

random forest

Comparing the two plots above: the global explanations across the two tree models (GMB vs Random Forest) are very similar - both models are tree ensembles, so the curvature (locally constant, discontinuous on facets) is similar. In the appendix, the code shows that the models perform equally well - it seems they learn similar things
